;; dice-forge.cnj
;; The Dice Forge — a workshop for polyhedral dice: define them, style them,
;; roll them. A complete project specification in a single .cnj file.
;;
;; ─── The role of this example ────────────────────────────────────────────
;;
;; This is the canonical SINGLE-FILE example: one .cnj carrying a whole
;; project from charter to handover-readiness, in the canonical section
;; order. For the multi-file layout — a project split across concern-bounded
;; .cnj files with a root anchor — see examples/conjurer-site/ instead. The
;; two examples are deliberately different projects: this one is a compact
;; browser app with a rich, self-contained domain; that one is a full-stack
;; site with an API and infrastructure.
;;
;; What this example showcases, section by section:
;;   §1 charter    — decision log, open questions, selective-materialisation outputs
;;   §2 assets     — a team standard (TSF++) and a design system as first-class assets
;;   §3 assume     — honest operative constraints (browser-only, no backend)
;;   §4 context    — a compact semantic frame
;;   §5 domain     — d/model with mechanically checkable invariants (Euler's
;;                   formula), tacit-knowledge annotations, shapes with sum-type
;;                   faces, a spell, an incantation with :expand :preview, a
;;                   faceted classification, and :forbids on the roll engine
;;   §6 frontend   — design tokens with an accessibility invariant, the die
;;                   editor as a w/flow, a breakpoint-based w/responsive
;;                   strategy, microcopy via w/copy
;;   §7 targets    — two thin materialisation surfaces; the probability model
;;                   deliberately stays Conjurer-only
;;   §8 foresight  — four graded candidates for what this project might become
;;   §9 coda       — the project's spells graduating into a practitioner grimoire

;; ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
;; SECTION 1 — CHARTER
;; ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

(charter "The Dice Forge"
  :version  "0.1.0"
  :created  "2026-07-05"
  :updated  "2026-07-13"
  :domain   "Polyhedral dice: their geometry, faces, values, and rolling —
             presented as a browser workshop for defining and rolling dice"

  :goals [
    "Let a user forge dice: choose a polyhedron, give its faces pips, numerals,
     symbols, or images, assign values or meanings, and pick its colours"
    "Roll any pool of forged dice with a satisfying animation and an outcome
     display that respects each die's semantics — sums for numeric dice,
     tallies for symbolic ones"
    "Keep the dice engine a pure functional core: same seed, same rolls,
     so fairness is a property test rather than a hope"
    "Serve as the canonical single-file .cnj example: every section of the
     canonical structure, exercised by a domain anyone can hold in their head"]

  :audience {:primary   :hobbyist-game-designer
             :secondary [:conjurer-learner :frontend-engineer]}

  :decisions [
    {:date "2026-07-05"
     :decision "Two packages: a pure core (geometry, faces, rolling) and a React
                app shell. The TSF++ standard enforces the boundary. The domain
                itself argues for this split — a roll is a pure function of a
                die and an RNG stream; only the shell owns entropy and effects."}
    {:date "2026-07-05"
     :decision "The core forbids unseeded randomness. Rolls take an injected,
                seedable RNG so that fairness (every face equiprobable) is
                verifiable by property test, and any roll can be replayed."}
    {:date "2026-07-05"
     :decision "Numeric AND symbolic dice from day one. Sum-type face content
                with per-die outcome semantics; Fudge dice (symbols carrying
                values) proved the model must support both at once."}
    {:date "2026-07-05"
     :decision "Browser-only. Dice sets persist to localStorage; no backend,
                no accounts. Anything that needs a server is a foresight
                candidate, not a launch feature."}
    {:date "2026-07-05"
     :decision "The percentile d% (two d10s read as one 00–99 outcome) is
                deferred: it introduces compound rolls, a concept the launch
                model deliberately excludes. Tracked as a graded candidate."}
    {:date "2026-07-07"
     :decision "d10 numbered 1–10; the face conventionally marked '0' is read
                as 10. Matches the majority of commercial dice and needs no
                special-casing in the outcome display. Recorded on
                polyhedron.pentagonal-trapezohedron in §5.2."}
    {:date "2026-07-07"
     :decision "Symbolic meanings are a fixed starter vocabulary for v1, not
                user-definable: :combat :defend :heal :star :critical :plus
                :minus :blank — exactly the meanings already exercised by
                this file's own dice. User-definable meanings become a
                foresight candidate if a second use case demands them, rather
                than an open-ended keyword space from day one."}
    {:date "2026-07-07"
     :decision "The workshop is responsive at one breakpoint (640px):
                mobile and desktop, no distinct tablet treatment for a
                personal tool with this small a surface. The editor flow's
                existing :linear model already shows one step at a time, so
                it needs no structural change; only the appearance swatch
                grid and the dice list reflow. See §6.3."}
    {:date "2026-07-09"
     :decision "The first materialisation of :core and :app followed the
                TSF++ architecture (functional core, Result-typed errors) but
                not its idioms: generated switches lacked absurd(), and
                interface was used where the standard requires type. The
                :tsfpp-standard asset had only named the standard, with a
                fictional :location and a seven-bullet summary — never given
                the generator the enforceable rule content. Replaced with
                :tsfpp-standard and :tsfpp-react, recovered directly from the
                @tsfpp/* packages' own source and enforcement config (see
                tsfpp.cnj). :app now references :tsfpp-react."}
    {:date "2026-07-10"
     :decision "Second materialise preflight surfaced two spec gaps and four
                tooling ambiguities, resolved as: (a) :dice-set-persistence
                was scoped in :app but manifested nowhere — now specified as
                the §6.6 conjure; first run is EMPTY, not seeded with the
                starter set, because §6.4's first-run copy is load-bearing.
                (b) workshop-responsive was manifested (§6.3) but missing
                from :app's :scope — scope corrected. (c) @tsfpp/* packages
                are private/unpublished, so core vendors a minimal prelude
                (absurd, Option, Result, pipe) and mirrors the eslint/tsconfig
                enforcement locally. (d) :app stays test-free — :produces
                [:spa] is the contract; app tests would be a spec change, not
                a generation-time override. (e) shadcn primitives are
                hand-vendored per the React profile's Rule 11.5. (f) Tooling
                pinned: npm workspaces, Vitest, fast-check."}
    {:date "2026-07-13"
     :decision "The first materialised app was visually flat — correctly so:
                the spec modelled appearance as one flat body token plus one
                pip token, and 'physical' roll feel was a style lean, not a
                requirement. Saying 'disappointing' to the generator would be
                blaming the build for the source. Upgraded with real dice as
                the bar (two-tone marble, metallic gold pips): appearance
                gains :finish (solid | gradient | marbled) with an optional
                :accent token; gold/amber primitives and three-stop ramps
                enter the theme; the contrast ensure now holds at every stop.
                Tumble animation and user-configurable roll effects moved
                from style leans to :requires; effect settings persist under
                their own versioned key; :reduced-motion still binds over
                every user setting. The :physics-3d candidate stays deferred
                — this is 2D CSS craft, not meshes. Core impact is one
                surgical delta (the die appearance type + its validation);
                only :app regenerates."}]

  :open []

  :outputs {
    :dice-domain-model :conjurer-only     ;; the authoritative spec — never code
    :probability-rules :conjurer-only     ;; fairness stays specification
    :core              :target-core       ;; declared in §7
    :app               :target-app}       ;; declared in §7

  :tags [:example :single-file :dice :typescript :react])

;; ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
;; SECTION 2 — ASSETS
;; ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

;; :tsfpp-standard and :tsfpp-react below are recovered assets, not hand
;; summarised ones — see tsfpp.cnj (sibling file) for the full recovery:
;; read directly from the @tsfpp/* packages' own enforcement config and
;; source (eslint rules, tsconfig flags, prelude exports, boundary usage),
;; not from a description of what the standard is called. This replaces an
;; earlier version of this asset that named a fictional :location and gave
;; only a seven-bullet architectural summary — which is why the first
;; materialisation of this file produced switches without absurd() and
;; interface instead of type: those are idiom-level rules, and idiom-level
;; rules only get followed when they are actually given to the generator,
;; not merely named.

(asset :tsfpp-standard
  :type        :code-standard
  :description "TSF++ (TypeScript Functional++) — a functional-core /
                imperative-shell TypeScript standard: correctness by
                construction, totality, immutability, referential
                transparency, exhaustiveness. Embodied by @tsfpp/prelude and
                @tsfpp/boundary; mechanically enforced by @tsfpp/eslint-config
                and @tsfpp/tsconfig. Recovered in full in tsfpp.cnj."
  :language    :typescript
  :location    "tsfpp.cnj"
  :version     "1.3.0 (spec) — prelude 1.7.0, boundary 1.2.0,
                eslint-config 1.0.1, tsconfig 1.0.0"
  :enforces    [
    "Illegal states unrepresentable: discriminated unions, never independent
     optional flags, for mutually exclusive data (Rule 1.1)"
    "Every switch over a discriminated union ends its default/else branch
     with `absurd(x)` on the `never`-narrowed remainder — not a bare
     `default: break`, not an unreachable-code comment (Rules 1.2/4.1)"
    "`type` aliases only — never `interface` — for every object/union shape
     (Rule 1.4)"
    "No `any`; no `!` non-null assertions; no `as` type assertions outside a
     single guarded smart-constructor per branded type (Rules 1.5/1.6)"
    "No `class`, `this`, `enum`, `namespace`, or `new` outside a commented
     adapter boundary (Rules 1.8/1.9)"
    "`const` only, deep `readonly`, no mutation (Rules 2.1–2.3)"
    "Explicit return type on every exported function; arity ≤ 3; complexity
     ≤ 10, nesting ≤ 4, ≤ 40 lines, one concern per function (Rules 3.1–3.4)"
    "No imperative loops — map/filter/reduce/recursion (Rule 4.2)"
    "Errors and absence as `Result<T,E>`/`Option<A>`, not exceptions; no
     `throw` outside an adapter boundary (Rule 6.2)"
    "Effectful capabilities (RNG entropy, storage) consumed through a
     structurally-typed port, injected at the composition root — never a
     concrete library imported into core logic"]
  :prohibits   [
    "`interface` declarations without a DEVIATION(1.4) comment"
    "A switch/if-chain over a union tag that does not narrow to `never` and
     call `absurd()` — the way generated code silently stops being
     exhaustive the moment a case is added"
    "`any`, bare `!`/`as`, `enum`, `namespace`, `class`, `this`"
    "Math.random or Date.now inside the core package"
    "Imperative mutation of shared state"
    "Default exports"]
  :applies-to  [:library :test-suite]
  :active-in   :project)

(asset :tsfpp-react
  :type        :code-standard
  :description "TSF++/React — the React profile layered on TSF++: render is a
                pure function of props/state; state is a liability, justified
                against an elimination ladder; `useEffect` is React's `goto`.
                Self-contained for a target's single :standard slot — restates
                the base rules most load-bearing for UI code. Recovered in
                full in tsfpp.cnj."
  :language    :typescript
  :location    "tsfpp.cnj"
  :version     "1.0.0"
  :enforces    [
    "Exhaustive switches end in `absurd(x)` — identical to base Rule 1.2/4.1,
     restated because it governs render branches and reducers too"
    "`type` aliases only, never `interface` — identical to base Rule 1.4"
    "Components are `const` arrow functions with explicit `ReactElement`
     return types — never `function` declarations or classes"
    "Props are `readonly`-fielded `type` aliases; mutually exclusive variants
     are a discriminated union, never optional flags"
    "Every piece of state is justified against the elimination ladder before
     introduction: derivable → URL → server data → form state → local
     `useState` → lifted → context/store"
    "`useEffect` only synchronises with systems outside React; never derives
     state, fetches data, or reacts to a user event; every subscribing effect
     returns a cleanup function"
    "Tailwind utilities and design tokens only — never hex codes or magic
     pixel values inline; variants via `cva`, never class-string
     concatenation"
    "Interactive elements are semantic HTML; every control has an associated
     label; keyboard navigation works for every flow"]
  :prohibits   [
    "Class components or `function`-declared components"
    "Optional-flag props for mutually exclusive variants"
    "`useEffect` for derived state, data fetching, or user-event reactions"
    "An effect that subscribes without returning a cleanup function"
    "Inline hex codes or pixel literals in `className`"
    "A `div`/`span` with an `onClick` standing in for a semantic element"]
  :applies-to  [:spa]
  :active-in   :project)

(asset :shadcn-tailwind
  :type        :component-library
  :description "shadcn/ui components on Tailwind — accessible primitives the
                app composes; die visuals are custom components on the same
                token base"
  :language    :typescript
  :location    "https://ui.shadcn.com"
  :enforces    [
    "Interactive components meet WCAG 2.1 AA"
    "All visual decisions reference design tokens, never raw values"]
  :applies-to  [:spa]
  :active-in   :project)

;; ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
;; SECTION 3 — ASSUMPTIONS
;; ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

(assume
  :environment    :browser-only-spa
  :scale          "Personal tool; tens of dice per user, not thousands"
  :team           {:size 1 :skill-level :senior}
  :infrastructure {:existing [:vite :react :tailwind :shadcn :localstorage]
                   :avoid    [:backend :accounts :databases]}
  :constraints    {:budget :none :timeline "A weekend project done well"}
  :negotiable     [:animation-library :icon-set]
  :non-negotiable [:seeded-rng-in-core :wcag-aa :reduced-motion-support])

;; ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
;; SECTION 4 — CONTEXT
;; ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

(context dice-workshop
  :domain      :tabletop-dice
  :entities    {:die  [:id :name :polyhedron :faces :semantics :appearance]
                :face [:position :content :value]
                :roll [:pool :seed :outcomes :total-or-tally]}
  :conventions {:values           :integers
                :randomness       :seeded-and-injected
                :face-positions   :one-indexed
                :outcome-display  :glyph-first}   ;; ⚄ before "5"
  :assumptions [
    "A die's identity is its definition, not any physical instance —
     rolling never mutates a die"
    "All seven standard RPG solids are isohedral: every face is
     geometrically equivalent, so a fair roll is equiprobable by shape"]
  :active-in   :session)

;; ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
;; SECTION 5 — DOMAIN
;; ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

;; ─── 5.1 The domain model ────────────────────────────────────────────────
;; d/model, not d/explore: there are no source documents here. This is
;; practitioner-authored knowledge, declared as such — the honest construct
;; for a domain the author already knows.

(d/model "Polyhedral Dice"
  :entities {
    :polyhedron {:type       :value-object
                 :attributes [:name :vertices :edges :face-count :face-shape]
                 :note       "Pure geometry — shared by every die of its shape"}

    :die        {:type       :aggregate-root
                 :attributes [:id :name :polyhedron :faces :semantics :appearance]
                 :lifecycle  [:draft :forged :retired]
                 :note       "A forged die is immutable; editing forges a
                              successor and retires the original, so past
                              rolls always reference the die that made them"}

    :face       {:type       :value-object
                 :attributes [:position :content :value]
                 :note       "Content is a sum type — see the face shape below"}

    :roll       {:type       :entity
                 :attributes [:id :pool :seed :rolled-at :outcomes]
                 :note       "Replayable: pool + seed fully determine outcomes"}}

  :relationships [
    {:from :die  :to :polyhedron :type :shaped-as   :cardinality :many-to-one}
    {:from :die  :to :face       :type :bears       :cardinality :one-to-many}
    {:from :roll :to :die        :type :throws      :cardinality :many-to-many}]

  :operations {
    :forge-die {:actors        [:user]
                :inputs        [:polyhedron :faces :semantics :appearance]
                :outputs       [:die]
                :preconditions ["face count equals the polyhedron's face-count"
                                "every face position 1..n is assigned exactly once"]
                :postconditions ["die enters :forged and becomes immutable"]}

    :roll-pool {:actors        [:user]
                :inputs        [:pool :rng-stream]
                :outputs       [:roll]
                :preconditions ["every die in the pool is :forged"]
                :postconditions ["one outcome per die; aggregation follows each
                                  die's semantics"]
                :invariants    ["rolling reads the RNG stream; it mutates nothing"]}}

  :invariants [
    "Euler's formula holds for every polyhedron: V − E + F = 2"
    "A die bears exactly as many faces as its polyhedron has"
    "On standard numeric dice, opposite faces sum to n+1 — except the d4,
     which has no opposite faces (see annotations)"
    "A fair die's faces are equiprobable: isohedral shape + unbiased RNG"]

  :manifest dice-domain)

;; ─── 5.2 Tacit knowledge the geometry alone doesn't say ─────────────────

(d/annotate dice-domain
  :annotations [
    {:target     "polyhedron.tetrahedron"
     :kind       :tacit-knowledge
     :note       "The d4 has no top face — it lands with a vertex up. Read the
                  upright value at the apex (or the base edge, on edge-numbered
                  variants). This is why the opposite-faces invariant exempts it:
                  a tetrahedron's faces have no opposites."
     :confidence :high}
    {:target     "die.numbering"
     :kind       :caveat
     :note       "Spindown d20s (numbers arranged in sequence for life-tracking)
                  violate the balanced-numbering convention on purpose. They are
                  legitimate dice but poor randomisers on physically imperfect
                  solids — worth a note in the editor if a user recreates one."
     :confidence :high}
    {:target     "polyhedron.pentagonal-trapezohedron"
     :kind       :context
     :note       "The d10 is the one standard die that is not Platonic — it is
                  isohedral (fair) without being regular. Fairness needs face
                  equivalence, not full regularity."
     :confidence :high}
    {:target     "polyhedron.pentagonal-trapezohedron.numbering"
     :kind       :context
     :note       "Numbered 1–10; the face conventionally marked '0' is read as
                  10 (charter decision, 2026-07-07). Resolves the launch's only
                  genuine numbering ambiguity — every other standard solid's
                  face values are unambiguous integers."
     :confidence :high}])

;; ─── 5.3 Shapes — what the data means ────────────────────────────────────

(shape face
  :fields {
    :position (integer :min 1)              ;; which face of the solid
    :content  (one-of                       ;; the sum type at the heart of the model
                {:pips    (integer :min 1 :max 9)}
                {:numeral (integer)}
                {:symbol  {:glyph   (string :single-grapheme)
                          :meaning (one-of :combat :defend :heal :star :critical
                                          :plus :minus :blank)}}   ;; closed v1 vocabulary — charter decision, 2026-07-07
                {:image   (url)})
    :value    (one-of (integer)             ;; plain numeric worth
                      {(keyword) (integer | percent)} ;; named values: {:def 5 :heal (percent 50)}
                      :none)}                          ;; pure symbol, tally only
  :invariants [
    "pip content implies value equals the pip count"
    "a face with :none value belongs only on a die with :symbolic semantics"]
  :examples [
    {:position 5 :content {:pips 5}                                :value 5}
    {:position 1 :content {:symbol {:glyph "⚔" :meaning :combat}} :value :none}
    {:position 3 :content {:symbol {:glyph "⛨" :meaning :defend}} :value {:def 5 :heal (percent 50)}}
    ;; Fudge/Fate face — the bridge case: a symbol that carries a number
    {:position 2 :content {:symbol {:glyph "+" :meaning :plus}}   :value 1}])

(shape die
  :fields {
    :id         (uuid)
    :name       (string :min-length 1 :max-length 40)
    :polyhedron (one-of :tetrahedron :cube :octahedron
                        :pentagonal-trapezohedron :dodecahedron :icosahedron)
    :faces      (list :of face)
    :semantics  (one-of :numeric :symbolic)
    :appearance {:finish (one-of :solid :gradient :marbled)  ;; default :solid
                 :body   (design-token)
                 :accent (design-token :optional)   ;; the second colour of a
                                                    ;; :gradient or :marbled
                                                    ;; finish; ignored by :solid
                 :pips   (design-token)}}
  :invariants [
    "faces count matches the polyhedron's face-count"
    ":numeric dice have an integer value on every face"
    "appearance references tokens, never raw colour values"
    ":gradient and :marbled finishes require an :accent token"
    "pips stay readable at every stop of the finish — contrast holds against
     body AND accent, not just the average"]
  :examples [
    {:name "Classic d6" :polyhedron :cube :semantics :numeric
     :faces "pips 1–6, opposite faces summing to 7"
     :appearance {:finish :solid :body :die.ivory :pips :die.pip-on-light}}
    ;; the two-tone-marble-with-gold-pips look of a real resin die:
    {:name "Gemini jade" :polyhedron :cube :semantics :numeric
     :faces "pips 1–6, opposite faces summing to 7"
     :appearance {:finish :marbled :body :die.jade :accent :die.onyx
                  :pips :die.pip-gold}}])

(shape roll-outcome
  :fields {
    :per-die (list :of {:die (uuid) :face face})
    :display (string)
    :result  (one-of {:total (integer)}                    ;; numeric pools sum
                     {:tally {(keyword) (integer)}})}      ;; symbolic pools count
  :examples [
    ;; the two aggregation semantics, rendered:
    {:display "⚄ + ⚅ = 11"            :result {:total 11}}
    {:display "⚔ ⚔ ⛨ → 2×combat, 1×defend (def 5, heal 50%)"
     :result  {:tally {:combat 2 :defend 1}}}
    {:display "+ − ␣ = 0"             :result {:total 0}}])   ;; 3dF, values sum
;; ✓ Three examples carry the whole outcome semantics: numeric dice sum,
;;   symbolic dice tally, and Fudge dice prove one die can be both.

;; ─── 5.4 Craft lore ──────────────────────────────────────────────────────

(lore dice-craft
  :observed-in ["physical dice manufacturing" "tabletop design practice"]
  :patterns [
    {:name      :balanced-numbering
     :when      "assigning values to a numeric die's faces"
     :apply     "Distribute so opposite faces sum to n+1 (d4 exempt)."
     :rationale "Balances the effect of any physical bias and matches every
                 die a user has ever held — violating it reads as wrong."}
    {:name      :standard-pip-arrangement
     :when      "rendering pip faces 1–9"
     :apply     "Use the canonical pip layouts (quincunx 5, two-column 6, …)."
     :rationale "Pip patterns are read as gestalts, not counted; a nonstandard
                 arrangement forces users to count."}]
  :anti-patterns [
    {:name    :low-contrast-pips
     :avoid   "Pip or glyph colour that fails contrast against the die body"
     :because "A die you cannot read at arm's length fails at its one job —
               contrast is enforced at the token layer (§6.1)."}]
  :active-in :session)

;; ─── 5.5 The spell: one reusable pattern for forging dice ───────────────

(spell forge-die [polyhedron & {:keys [face-style semantics appearance]
                                :or   {face-style :numerals
                                       semantics  :numeric
                                       appearance {:finish :solid
                                                   :body   :die.ivory
                                                   :pips   :die.pip-on-light}}}]
  :doc "Forge a die of the given solid with the workshop's defaults baked in:
        balanced numbering per the dice-craft lore, token-based appearance,
        and faces generated to match the polyhedron's face count."
  (conjure die
    :shaped-as  polyhedron
    :faces      (generate-faces polyhedron face-style)   ;; balanced per lore
    :semantics  semantics
    :appearance appearance
    :within     (ensure :structural ["face count = polyhedron face-count"]
                        :verify-via [:tests])))

;; Casting it: the invariant part lives in the spell; each cast is the delta.
(forge-die :cube)                                          ;; a classic pipped d6
(forge-die :icosahedron :face-style :numerals)             ;; a standard d20
(forge-die :cube
  :face-style {:symbols [{:glyph "+" :meaning :plus  :value  1}
                         {:glyph "+" :meaning :plus  :value  1}
                         {:glyph "−" :meaning :minus :value -1}
                         {:glyph "−" :meaning :minus :value -1}
                         {:glyph "␣" :meaning :blank :value  0}
                         {:glyph "␣" :meaning :blank :value  0}]}
  :semantics :numeric)                                     ;; a Fudge die: dF
(forge-die :cube
  :face-style {:symbols [{:glyph "⚔" :meaning :combat}
                         {:glyph "⚔" :meaning :combat}
                         {:glyph "⚔" :meaning :combat}
                         {:glyph "⛨" :meaning :defend :value {:def 5 :heal (percent 50)}}
                         {:glyph "⛨" :meaning :defend :value {:def 5 :heal (percent 50)}}
                         {:glyph "★" :meaning :critical}]}
  :semantics :symbolic
  :appearance {:finish :marbled :body :die.crimson :accent :die.onyx
               :pips :die.pip-gold})     ;; a combat die — crimson/onyx marble,
                                         ;; gold glyphs, like the real thing

;; ─── 5.6 The incantation: the standard set from one expansion ────────────

(incantation standard-dice-set [_]
  :doc "The seven-piece RPG set minus the percentile die (deferred — §8):
        one forge-die cast per standard solid."
  :expands-to
    (for [solid [{:polyhedron :tetrahedron              :sides 4  :v 4  :e 6  :f 4}
                 {:polyhedron :cube                     :sides 6  :v 8  :e 12 :f 6}
                 {:polyhedron :octahedron               :sides 8  :v 6  :e 12 :f 8}
                 {:polyhedron :pentagonal-trapezohedron :sides 10 :v 12 :e 20 :f 10}
                 {:polyhedron :dodecahedron             :sides 12 :v 20 :e 30 :f 12}
                 {:polyhedron :icosahedron              :sides 20 :v 12 :e 30 :f 20}]]
      (forge-die (:polyhedron solid)
        :face-style (if (= 6 (:sides solid)) :pips :numerals))))

;; Phase 1 — deterministic, inspectable, nothing manifested:
(standard-dice-set :expand :preview)
;; => (forge-die :tetrahedron              :face-style :numerals)   ;; d4
;;    (forge-die :cube                     :face-style :pips)       ;; d6
;;    (forge-die :octahedron               :face-style :numerals)   ;; d8
;;    (forge-die :pentagonal-trapezohedron :face-style :numerals)   ;; d10
;;    (forge-die :dodecahedron             :face-style :numerals)   ;; d12
;;    (forge-die :icosahedron              :face-style :numerals)   ;; d20
;; ✓ The exact six casts that WOULD run, visible before anything is forged.
;;   Note the vertex/edge/face data in the expansion source: every solid
;;   satisfies V − E + F = 2, and the generated test suite asserts it.

;; Phase 2 — the generative act, against an expansion already seen to be sound:
(standard-dice-set :manifest starter-set)

;; ─── 5.7 Classification: dice are faceted, not a tree ────────────────────

(t/facet "Dice Classification"
  :purpose "Filter and browse the workshop's dice along independent dimensions"
  :facets {
    :polyhedron   {:values [:tetrahedron :cube :octahedron
                            :pentagonal-trapezohedron :dodecahedron :icosahedron]
                   :criterion "The solid"                     :cardinality :one}
    :face-content {:values [:pips :numerals :symbols :images]
                   :criterion "What the faces show"           :cardinality :one}
    :semantics    {:values [:numeric :symbolic]
                   :criterion "How outcomes aggregate"        :cardinality :one}
    :palette      {:values :open
                   :criterion "Appearance theme"              :cardinality :one}}
  :constraints [
    {:rule ":pips content implies :numeric semantics" :facets [:face-content :semantics]}]
  :manifest dice-facets)
;; ✓ A pipped d6 and a skull-faced d6 differ on one facet, not in species —
;;   forcing this into a tree would have nested appearance under content
;;   under solid, uselessly.

;; ─── 5.8 The roll engine — where :forbids earns its keep ─────────────────

(conjure roll-engine
  :accepts  {:pool (list :of die) :rng :seeded-stream}
  :returns  roll-outcome
  :requires [:pure-function :replayable-rolls :per-semantics-aggregation]
  :forbids  [:unseeded-randomness :thrown-exceptions :mutation-of-dice]
  :within (ensure
    :structural  ["engine lives in the core package; imports no shell modules"]
    :behavioural [
      "with a fixed seed, the same pool rolls the same outcomes, always"
      "10,000 seeded rolls of any starter-set die land every face within
       3σ of uniform — the fairness property test"
      "a numeric pool reports {:total}; a symbolic pool reports {:tally};
       a Fudge pool reports {:total} because its symbols carry values"]
    :verify-via   [:tests :llm]
    :on-violation :halt)
  :manifest roll-engine)
;; ✓ :forbids is the load-bearing negative here: Math.random anywhere in the
;;   core would make the fairness test meaningless. The prohibition shapes
;;   generation up front; the property test verifies it after.

;; ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
;; SECTION 6 — FRONTEND DESIGN
;; ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

;; ─── 6.1 Tokens: die appearance as a design system ──────────────────────

;; Upgraded 2026-07-13: the first materialised app was visually flat because
;; this token set could only EXPRESS flat — one body colour, one pip colour.
;; Real dice (the bar for this workshop) are two-tone marble, swirled resin,
;; metallic gold pips. Three-stop ramps make depth and gradients expressible;
;; gold and amber join the palette; finishes become named token-layer
;; treatments. All CSS — layered gradients and blends, no image assets.

(w/tokens "Forge Theme"
  :primitives {:color {:ivory   {300 "#faf7f0" 500 "#f5f0e6" 700 "#e6dcc8"}
                       :crimson {300 "#c04a5e" 500 "#9b1c31" 700 "#6e1424"}
                       :indigo  {300 "#5c6cae" 500 "#3b4a8c" 700 "#2a3567"}
                       :jade    {300 "#4d9583" 500 "#2e6e5e" 700 "#1f4f43"}
                       :onyx    {300 "#3a3a44" 500 "#1c1c22" 700 "#111116"}
                       :gold    {300 "#e8c96a" 500 "#c9a227" 700 "#96771a"}
                       :amber   {300 "#d99a4e" 500 "#b8742c" 700 "#8a561f"}}
               :space  [0 4 8 16 24 32]
               :radius [8 12 16]}
  :semantic   {:die     {:ivory        "@color.ivory.500"
                         :crimson      "@color.crimson.500"
                         :indigo       "@color.indigo.500"
                         :jade         "@color.jade.500"
                         :onyx         "@color.onyx.500"
                         :amber        "@color.amber.500"
                         :pip-on-light "@color.onyx.500"
                         :pip-on-dark  "@color.ivory.500"
                         :pip-gold     "@color.gold.500"}
               ;; the app chrome around the dice — a bench, not a dashboard
               :surface {:bench-from "@color.onyx.700"
                         :bench-to   "@color.indigo.700"
                         :card       "@color.onyx.500"
                         :edge       "@color.gold.700"}}
  :components {:die-face {:radius "@radius.2" :glyph-scale 0.62
                          ;; finishes are token-layer treatments, so the
                          ;; contrast ensure below governs them too:
                          :finishes {:solid    "body colour with a soft
                                                top-light vignette (300 stop
                                                catching the light, 700 in
                                                the shadow) — flat fills read
                                                as plastic, not resin"
                                     :gradient "linear 135°, body → accent"
                                     :marbled  "body base with accent veins —
                                                layered CSS gradients and
                                                blend modes, no images"}
                          :pip-metallic "pips/numerals in @die.pip-gold carry
                                         a radial highlight (gold.300 core →
                                         gold.700 rim) — gold must read as
                                         metal, not mustard"}}
  :export-as  [:css-custom-properties :tailwind-config]
  :within (ensure
    :structural   ["every (body, pip) pairing offered by the picker meets
                    4.5:1 contrast — and for :gradient and :marbled finishes
                    the rule holds at EVERY stop: the pip must clear both the
                    body colour and the accent colour"]
    :verify-via   [:tests]
    :on-violation :halt)
  :manifest forge-theme)
;; ✓ Readability is correctness for a die. The contrast rule lives at the
;;   token layer, so the colour picker can only offer legal pairings —
;;   the anti-pattern in the dice-craft lore, made unrepresentable.

;; ─── 6.2 The die editor as a flow ────────────────────────────────────────

(w/flow forge-a-die
  :state-model :linear
  :steps [
    {:name :choose-solid    :screen "Pick the polyhedron — six solids, previewed in 3D-ish CSS"
     :validates [:one-selected]                     :on-error :inline-correction}
    {:name :face-content    :screen "Pips, numerals, symbols, or images"
     :validates [:style-legal-for-solid]            :on-error :inline-correction}
    {:name :values-meanings :screen "Assign values or meanings per face"
     :validates [:every-face-assigned :numeric-dice-fully-valued]
     :on-error :inline-correction}
    {:name :appearance      :screen "Finish first — solid, gradient, or marbled,
                                     previewed live on the die — then body,
                                     accent, and pip material from the legal
                                     pairings"
     :validates [:tokens-only :contrast-at-every-stop] :on-error :inline-correction}
    {:name :review-forge    :screen "The die, rendered and rollable once for feel"
     :on-error :save-and-recover}]
  :persistence :session          ;; a half-forged die survives navigation
  :optimistic  false
  :surface     [:happy-path :error-paths :recovery]
  :manifest    editor-flow)
;; Editing a forged die re-enters this flow with fields pre-filled; forging
;; from the review step retires the original — the immutability decision
;; from the domain model (§5.1), surfaced as UX.

;; ─── 6.3 Responsive strategy ──────────────────────────────────────────────
;; The charter's third open question, resolved 2026-07-07: one breakpoint,
;; two contexts. A personal tool this small doesn't earn a tablet treatment.

(w/responsive dice-workshop-app
  :strategy    :breakpoint-based
  :breakpoints [640]
  :contexts    [:mobile :desktop]
  :transform   {:mobile {:layout :single-column
                         :reflow [{:from :appearance-token-grid :to :scrollable-row}
                                  {:from :dice-list-grid          :to :single-column-list}]}}
  :priority    :content
  :manifest    workshop-responsive)
;; ✓ editor-flow's :state-model :linear already presents one step at a time,
;;   so the flow itself needs no mobile-specific structure — only two
;;   genuinely dense widgets reflow: the appearance token grid (§6.2 step 4)
;;   and the workshop's dice list, both of which assume desktop width today.

;; ─── 6.4 Microcopy for the states the happy path never shows ────────────

(w/copy dice-workshop-app
  :surfaces   [:empty-states :error-messages :buttons :confirmations]
  :voice      {:tone :warm :person :second :formality :casual}
  :for-component editor-flow
  :principles [:clarity :blameless-errors :consistent-terms]
  :locale     :en
  :manifest   workshop-copy)
;; Expected register, by example:
;;   first-run empty state — "No dice yet. Forge your first."
;;   no-results (filtered) — "No dice match those facets — clear a filter?"
;;   delete confirmation   — "Retire this die? Past rolls keep their record."
;;   roll button           — "Roll" (it does not need to be cleverer than that)

;; ─── 6.5 The roll experience ─────────────────────────────────────────────

;; Upgraded 2026-07-13: "physical" was a :style lean before, and the first
;; materialisation read it minimally — a colour flash, no tumble. What makes
;; a roll feel like a roll is now :requires, not vibes.

(conjure roll-experience
  :requires [
    :outcome-display-per-semantics
    :keyboard-operable
    :tumble-animation       ;; dice visibly shake, tumble with FACES CYCLING
                            ;; while airborne (a rotate alone is not a
                            ;; tumble), then settle into the outcome
    :configurable-effects]  ;; the user tunes the roll from a small settings
                            ;; surface next to the roll button: speed, motion
                            ;; intensity, glow on/off
  :style {
    :feel      "physical — dice tumble, settle, then the outcome line appears"
    :duration  (prefer (ms 900))          ;; default; user-tunable ~300–1500
    :effects   {:settle  (prefer :overshoot-wobble)   ;; lands with a bounce
                :stagger (prefer :per-die-offset)     ;; pools land one by one
                :glow    (prefer :soft-glow-on-final-face)}  ;; token-coloured
    :settings-persistence (prefer "dice-forge.settings.v1")
                            ;; own versioned localStorage key, same discipline
                            ;; as §6.6 — never inside the dice envelope
    :library   (allow :framer-motion)     ;; illustrative — any capable lib
    :reduced-motion (certain :fade-only)} ;; binding — and it overrides EVERY
                                          ;; user effect setting; a11y is not
                                          ;; a preference among preferences
  :manifest roll-experience)
;; ✓ All three certainty markers in one :style map, each where it belongs:
;;   the a11y behaviour is bound, the timing and effects are leans, the
;;   library is open. The tumble itself is :requires — load-bearing.

;; ─── 6.6 Persistence: the one state that outlives a session ─────────────
;; Added 2026-07-10: :app's scope always listed :dice-set-persistence, but
;; nothing in the file manifested it — the only scope item without a spec.
;; Caught by materialise preflight (:on-unresolved :halt did its job);
;; specified here rather than left to generation-time inference.

(conjure dice-set-persistence
  :requires [
    :versioned-envelope        ;; {:version 1 :dice [...]} — the schema is
                               ;; versioned BEFORE history accretes, per the
                               ;; roll-history candidate's own note (§8)
    :forged-and-retired-only   ;; drafts are ephemeral — editor-flow's
                               ;; :persistence :session already covers them;
                               ;; retired dice ARE persisted, so forge-lineage
                               ;; (§5.1: editing forges a successor) survives
                               ;; a reload
    :validate-on-load]         ;; malformed or absent storage must never
                               ;; crash the app or throw
  :forbids [
    :destructive-migration]    ;; never overwrite an envelope this code
                               ;; cannot read (an unknown, newer :version) —
                               ;; fall back to in-memory empty, leave the
                               ;; stored value untouched
  :style {
    :medium       (certain :localstorage)     ;; charter: no backend, ever
    :key          (prefer "dice-forge.dice.v1")
    :on-first-run (certain :empty)}  ;; absent storage = empty collection —
                                     ;; §6.4's first-run copy ("No dice yet.
                                     ;; Forge your first.") is load-bearing;
                                     ;; seeding the starter set would make
                                     ;; that state unreachable
  :returns "load: Result<ReadonlyArray<Die>, PersistenceError>;
            save: Result<Unit, PersistenceError> — a quota or serialisation
            failure surfaces as an Err the UI can show; the in-memory forge
            still succeeds"
  :manifest dice-set-persistence)

;; ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
;; SECTION 7 — TARGETS (selective materialisation)
;; ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
;; Only two surfaces become code. The domain model and the probability rules
;; remain Conjurer — the specification the implementation is measured against.

(target :core
  :language  :typescript
  :runtime   :browser
  :standard  :tsfpp-standard
  :produces  [:library :types :test-suite]
  :scope     [:polyhedron :die :face :roll-engine :dice-facets]
  :from      dice-domain
  :style     {:errors :result-type :rng :injected-interface
              ;; The @tsfpp/* packages are private and unpublished (see
              ;; tsfpp.cnj's :location note), so the standard's vocabulary is
              ;; vendored, not installed: a minimal local prelude implementing
              ;; exactly what this code uses (absurd, Option, Result, pipe),
              ;; with the standard's rules applied via a local eslint
              ;; flat-config + tsconfig mirroring @tsfpp/eslint-config's
              ;; base.ts and @tsfpp/tsconfig's base flags.
              :prelude        :vendored-minimal
              :test-runner    :vitest
              :property-tests :fast-check}
  :via       :direct
  :manifest  target-core)

(target :app
  :language  :typescript
  :framework :react
  :runtime   :browser
  :standard  :tsfpp-react
  :produces  [:spa]
  :scope     [:editor-flow :roll-experience :forge-theme :workshop-copy
              :workshop-responsive :dice-set-persistence]
  :from      dice-domain
  :style     {:build :vite :css :tailwind :components :shadcn
              ;; shadcn primitives are hand-vendored local components in the
              ;; shadcn idiom (no CLI/registry fetch at materialise time) —
              ;; which is also what the React profile's own Rule 11.5 asks:
              ;; vendored into the repo, subject to the same rules as
              ;; application code.
              :persistence :localstorage
              :aesthetic "a craftsman's bench, not a dashboard: deep
                          bench-gradient surfaces (@surface tokens), gold
                          edge accents, soft shadows, generous radius — the
                          dice are the jewellery, the chrome recedes"}
  :via       :direct
  :manifest  target-app)

;; Everything not in a :scope above — the invariants, the annotations, the
;; fairness rules, the lore — stays in this file, authoritative and uncoded.

;; ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
;; SECTION 8 — FORESIGHT: what the forge might become
;; ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

(f/candidate :dice-notation
  :label   "Parse standard dice notation — '3d6+2', '4dF', 'd20 adv'"
  :added   "2026-07-05" :status :proposed
  :scores  {:feasibility 7 :elegance 8 :containment 8 :value 8}
  :rationale "The lingua franca of every tabletop table; a text box that rolls
              '3d6+2' meets users where they already are. Deferred because the
              grammar (modifiers, advantage, exploding dice) deserves design,
              not a launch-week regex."
  :conditions ["editor and roll flows stable" "grammar scope decided"]
  :cluster :input)

(f/candidate :roll-history
  :label   "Roll history with per-die statistics and a fairness view"
  :added   "2026-07-05" :status :proposed
  :scores  {:feasibility 8 :elegance 7 :containment 8 :value 6}
  :rationale "Replayable rolls make history nearly free to record, and a
              distribution chart makes the fairness property visible to users,
              not just to tests. Deferred as pure addition — nothing at launch
              depends on it."
  :conditions ["localStorage schema versioned before history accretes"]
  :cluster :analysis)

(f/candidate :physics-3d
  :label   "Physically simulated 3D rolls (WebGL) replacing the CSS tumble"
  :added   "2026-07-05" :status :proposed
  :scores  {:feasibility 4 :elegance 6 :containment 6 :value 6}
  :rationale "The most-requested feature of every dice app and the most
              expensive: a physics engine, meshes per solid, and a subtle
              honesty question — display physics must not replace the seeded
              engine as the source of outcomes. Kept because it is the
              delight ceiling; deferred because everything else is cheaper."
  :conditions ["outcome-from-engine, animation-as-replay architecture proven"]
  :cluster :experience)
;; Boundary note, 2026-07-13: the roll-experience upgrade (§6.5 — required
;; tumble, configurable effects) is deliberately still the CSS side of this
;; line. It raises the 2D craft; it does not sneak this candidate in early.

(f/candidate :percentile-d100
  :label   "The percentile pair: two d10s read as one 00–99 outcome"
  :added   "2026-07-05" :status :proposed
  :scores  {:feasibility 8 :elegance 6 :containment 7 :value 5}
  :rationale "Completes the classic seven-piece set (charter decision,
              2026-07-05). Deferred because it introduces compound rolls —
              one outcome from two dice — which the launch model deliberately
              excludes; admitting it early would complicate every outcome
              display for one die."
  :conditions ["a second compound-roll use case appears (e.g. advantage),
                justifying the concept properly"]
  :cluster :input)

;; ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
;; SECTION 9 — CODA: the workshop's spells, graduated into a spellbook
;; ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
;; When a second project wants dice (§8's candidates hint at one), the
;; expertise in this file does not get re-derived — it gets packaged:

(grimoire dice-forge
  :namespace "dice/"
  :version   "0.1.0"
  :doc       "The Dice Forge spellbook: forging, classifying, and rolling
              polyhedral dice, with the craft lore that keeps them honest"
  :provides  [dice/forge-die dice/standard-dice-set]
  :lore      [dice-craft]
  :shapes    [dice/die dice/face dice/roll-outcome])

(asset :dice-forge-grimoire
  :type        :grimoire
  :description "Dice-domain spells, lore, and shapes from The Dice Forge"
  :location    "grimoires/dice-forge.cnj"
  :version     "0.1.0"
  :applies-to  [:library :spa]
  :active-in   :project)
;; ✓ The single-file project ends where the language's founding metaphor
;;   closes: practitioners do not only read grimoires — they write them.
